rctic Lands}} [[Crozet Islands]]||{{Nts|30}}||{{Nts|18}}||{{flag|French Southern and Antarctic Lands}}||{{flagicon|France}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]]||[[Africa]]\n|-\n|10||{{flagicon|French Southern and Antarctic Lands}} [[\u00cele Saint-Paul|Saint Paul]]{{\\}}[[\u00cele Amsterdam]]||colspan=\"2\"| {{nts|28}}||{{flag|French Southern and Antarctic Lands}}||{{flagicon|France}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]]||[[Africa]]\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== See also ==\n*{{Annotated link|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronamap.it Corona MAP] - Daily updated interactive free map of the whole world. \n* [https://thevirustracker.com/coronavirus-timeline-map Coronavirus Timeline Map] \u2013 Maps the timeline of the Coronavirus infections, deaths and recoveries.\n* [https://www.wolframcloud.com/obj/examples/COVID19World Epidemic data for COVID-19] \u2013 Maps total cases of coronavirus in the world, China and the United States, along with patient data.\n* [https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] by [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n* [https://coronamapper.com CoronaMapper] \u2013 Map with several updated statistics\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory| ]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters by country|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters by country|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Details regarding the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|Map of confirmed cases of COVID-19 per capita (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#900000|1,000+ confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#c80200|100\u20131,000 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|10\u2013100 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201310 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ffdfe0|>0\u20131 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#eee|No confirmed cases or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map.svg|thumb|Total confirmed cases of COVID-19 by country and territory (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#300000|100,000+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#510000|10,000-99,999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|1,000\u20139,999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|100\u2013999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|10\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#eee|No confirmed cases or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map Total Deaths per Capita.svg|thumb|Total confirmed deaths per capita of COVID-19 by country and territory (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#980043|100+ deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#dd1c77|10\u2013100 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#df65b0|1\u201310 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#c994c7|0.1\u20131 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#d4b9da|0.01\u20130.1 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#d1d0e6|>0\u20130.01 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#e0e0e0|No deaths or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\nThis article documents countries and territories affected by and their responses to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]] responsible for the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing 2019\u201320 pandemic]] first detected in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]. It may not include all the most up-to-date major responses and measures.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n{{clear|right}}\n{{clear|left}}\n\n== Pandemic by country and territory ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data|India cases 2,032 Deaths: 58=}}\n=== Confirmed cases ===\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|time|editlink=|ref=no}} on {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, a total of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|confirmed|editlink=|ref=no}} cases were confirmed in 204 countries and territories, including five cruise ships. There were {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|active|editlink=|ref=no}} active cases and {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|deaths|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths, with a mortality rate of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ratio|editlink=|ref=no}}.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|editlink=|ref=}}\n\n=== Africa ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa}}\nCases have been confirmed in most African countries and territories. According to Michael Yao, WHO's head of emergency operations in Africa, early detection is vital because the continent's health systems \"are already overwhelmed by many ongoing disease outbreaks\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51403865 |title=Coronavirus: Could African countries cope with an outbreak? |date=6 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308100334/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51403865 |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Kaamil|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/20/worlds-most-vulnerable-in-third-wave-for-covid-19-support-warn-experts|title=World's most vulnerable in 'third wave' for Covid-19 support, experts warn|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> As of 31 March, cases have been confirmed in all African nations except for [[Comoros]], [[Lesotho]], [[Malawi]], [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]], [[South Sudan]] and the disputed state of the [[Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic]]. There have been no reported cases in the territory of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]].\n\n=== Asia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia}}\nA cluster of mysterious [[pneumonia]] cases was detected in December 2019 in [[Wuhan]] and eventually spread to the rest of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in China|China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-12-31/Authorities-begin-testing-after-pneumonia-cases-in-central-China-MRPvtFbCve/index.html|title=27 cases of viral pneumonia reported in central China's Wuhan City|website=news.cgtn.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Afterwards, many other Asian countries started to confirm cases, with some of the most affected countries being [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], [[Malaysia]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]]. Sophisticated modelling of the outbreak suggests that while the number of cases in China would have been many times higher without interventions such as early detection and isolation of the infected, 66% fewer people would have been infected if China had implemented measures as little as a week earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sample|first=Ian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/research-finds-huge-impact-of-interventions-on-spread-of-covid-19|title=Research finds huge impact of interventions on spread of Covid-19|date=2020-03-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> As of 21 March, cases have been reported in all Asian countries except for [[Tajikistan]] and [[Turkmenistan]], while [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea|North Korea]] and [[Yemen]] have suspected cases. No cases have been reported in the disputed states [[Abkhazia]], [[Republic of Artsakh|Artsakh]], and [[South Ossetia]] and external territories [[Christmas Island]] and [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]].\n\n=== Europe ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe}}\nInitial cases in Europe were reported [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|in France]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]] and other countries with a relatively low number of cases. On 21 February, a large outbreak was [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|reported in Italy]], mostly in the north near [[Milan]]. Cases grew rapidly as the outbreak spread across Europe. Cases have been reported in all European countries after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montenegro|Montenegro]] reported a case on 17 March, and in all European territories after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] on 19 March, the disputed state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Transnistria|Transnistria]] on 21 March<ref>[http://a-tv.md/eng/index.php?newsid=78329 AccentTv Another 14 cases of coronavirus have been confirmed in Moldova. Total number reached 80]</ref> and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands|\u00c5land Islands]] on 22 March reported cases. No cases have been reported in [[Svalbard]], [[Alderney]], and [[Sark]]. The [[World Health Organization|WHO]] has declared [[Europe]] as the new centre of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|virus]] after the situation improved in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51876784|title=Europe 'now epicentre of coronavirus pandemic'|date=2020-03-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> As of 24 March, there have been 200,000 confirmed cases and 10,400 deaths in Europe; out of these, 64,000 cases and 6,100 deaths were in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://interaktiv.morgenpost.de/corona-virus-karte-infektionen-deutschland-weltweit/|title=Coronavirus: Echtzeit-Karte zeigt Zahl der Infektionen in Deutschland, Europa und weltweit|accessdate=2020-03-24 <!--02:30 UTC-->}}</ref> A study of three municipalities in Italy has indicated that the number of deaths may be underreported by a factor of four.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/politica/20_marzo_26/the-real-death-toll-for-covid-19-is-at-least-4-times-the-official-numbers-b5af0edc-6eeb-11ea-925b-a0c3cdbe1130.shtml?fbclid=IwAR2kP22GAIgiv3hiaJLVXgtZ9aZDxlwk5i7R1dYv1tCUalRO72eT23q2FzI|title=The real death toll for Covid-19 is at least 4 times the official numbers|first1=Claudio|last1=Cancelli|first2=Luca|last2=Foresti|publisher=Corriere Della Sera|date=2020-03-26|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America}}\nThe first cases in North America were reported [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]] in January 2020. Cases were reported in all North American countries after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis|Saint Kitts and Nevis]] confirmed a case on 25 March, and in all North American territories except [[Bonaire]], [[Saba]], and [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]] (as of 1 April).\n\n=== Oceania ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania}}\nCases have been confirmed in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia|Australia]], Easter Island, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji|Fiji]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Polynesia|French Polynesia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam|Guam]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Caledonia|New Caledonia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|New Zealand]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Papua New Guinea|Papua New Guinea]]. The first confirmed case was in Melbourne, Victoria on 25 January.<ref name=Case1>{{Cite web |url=https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/first-confirmed-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-australia|title=First confirmed case of novel coronavirus in Australia|date=25 January 2020|website=Australian Government Department of Health |access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215171557/https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/first-confirmed-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-australia|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many small Pacific island nations have thus far avoided the outbreak by closing their borders. Cases have been reported in all Oceanian sovereign states except [[Kiribati]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[Federated States of Micronesia]], [[Nauru]], [[Palau]], [[Samoa]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Tonga]], [[Tuvalu]], and [[Vanuatu]], and have not been reported in the associated states of [[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]]. No cases have been reported in the [[Autonomous Region of Bougainville]], [[Norfolk Island]], [[Wallis and Futuna]], [[Tokelau]], [[Pitcairn Islands]], and [[American Samoa]].\n\n===South America===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America}}\nAs of 19 March, cases have been confirmed in all South American countries: [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Argentina|Argentina]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brazil|Brazil]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|Bolivia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile|Chile]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Colombia|Colombia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ecuador|Ecuador]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guyana|Guyana]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Paraguay|Paraguay]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Peru|Peru]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Suriname|Suriname]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uruguay|Uruguay]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela|Venezuela]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Guiana|the French overseas department of French Guiana]]. No cases have been reported in the [[Falkland Islands]], but there have been suspected cases.\n\nThe coronavirus was first reported in South America on 26 February when Brazil confirmed a case in S\u00e3o Paulo. Since then, governments across the region have taken an array of actions to protect their citizens and contain the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.as-coa.org/articles/where-coronavirus-latin-america|title=Where Is the Coronavirus in Latin America?|first1=Luisa|last1=Horwitz|first2=Paola|last2=Nagovitch|first3=Holly K.|last3=Sonnel|first4=Carin|last4=Zissis|website=AS/COA}}</ref>\n\n=== International conveyance ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nThe outbreak spread to several cruise ships including the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|''Diamond Princess'']], the ''[[Grand Princess]]'', the ''[[World Dream]]'', the [[MS Westerdam|MS ''Westerdam'']] and the [[MS Braemar|MS ''Braemar'']].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51433079 |title=Thousands on cruise free to go after virus tests |date=10 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222232522/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51433079 |archive-date=22 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Marsh |first=Sarah |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/23/coronavirus-outbreak-woman-tests-positive-after-disembarking-diamond-princess-live-news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: four cruise ship passengers test positive in UK \u2013 live news |date=23 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223111701/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/23/coronavirus-outbreak-woman-tests-positive-after-disembarking-diamond-princess-live-news |archive-date=23 February 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/22/coronavirus-cruise-ships-westerdam-passengers-lives-still-affected/4841819002/ |title=Coronavirus still wreaking havoc on lives of Westerdam passengers despite no cases on ship |last=Hines |first=Morgan |website=USA Today |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223002910/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/22/coronavirus-cruise-ships-westerdam-passengers-lives-still-affected/4841819002/ |archive-date=23 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/2020/mar/12/breaking-five-bahamas-bound-cruise-ship-test-posit/|title=Cruise Ship Carrying Persons With Coronavirus 'Will Not Be Permitted To Dock'|date=13 March 2020|website=The Tribune|language=en}}</ref>\n\nCruise operators have started to either cancel or change their itineraries as countries across the world implement travel restrictions to curb the disease spread. Ports are refusing to accept cruise ships that have been either to Chinese ports or are carrying Chinese passengers during the outbreak.\n\nThe [[Cruise Lines International Association|Cruise Lines International Association (CLIA)]], which represents 90% of cruise operators, announced the various precautionary measures being implemented by its members. All passengers who have travelled to or visited/transited through [[China]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] within 14 days before embarkation will be denied entry into cruise ships. Any persons in close contact with either suspected or diagnosed cases of coronavirus infection will also be denied entry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ship-technology.com/features/coronavirus-outbreak-2019-ncov-impact-cruise-operators-measures-tourism/|title=Coronavirus outbreak: How the 2019-nCoV is affecting the cruise industry|date=9 March 2020|website=Ship Technology|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Entities without confirmed cases ==\nBelow is a list of countries and territories with no confirmed cases of COVID-19, in order of greatest population.\n\nLocations with suspected cases are in ''italics'' and noted with an asterisk (*).\n\n=== UN member states ===\nAs of 31 March 2020, 19 sovereign states (all in [[Africa]], [[Asia]], or [[Oceania]]) have not confirmed any cases of COVID-19. Below is a list of these countries, in order of greatest population.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.worldometers.info/geography/alphabetical-list-of-countries/ |title=Population of all countries |work=Worldometer |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!#