ones/g4 http://www.lg.com/us/mobile-phones/g4]\n|modelnumber=LG H810 <small>(AT&T)</small><br>LG H811 <small>(T-Mobile)</small><br>LG H815 <small>(international)</small><br>LG H815T <small>(Hong Kong)</small><br>LG H818 <small>(China)</small><br>LG H819 <small>(China)</small><br>LG VS986 <small>(Verizon)</small><br>LG LS991 <small>(Sprint)</small><br>LG US991 <small>(US Cellular)</small><br>\n<ref name=\"LG G4\">{{cite web|title=LG G4 Specs|url=https://www.phonearena.com/phones/LG-G4_id9104|website=phoneArena|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Download LG G4 Stock Firmware\">{{cite web|title=Download LG G4 Stock Firmware|url=http://rootmygalaxy.net/download-lg-g4-stock-firmware-all-variants/|website=phoneArena|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nThe '''LG G4''' is an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[smartphone]] developed by [[LG Electronics]] as part of the [[LG G series]]. Unveiled on 28 April 2015 and first released in [[South Korea]] on 29 April 2015 and widely released in June 2015, as the successor to 2014's [[LG G3|G3]]. The G4 is primarily an evolution of the G3, with revisions to its overall design, display and camera.\n\nThe G4 received mixed to positive reviews; while praising the G4's display quality, camera, and overall performance, critics characterized the G4 as being a robust device that did not contain enough substantial changes or innovation over its predecessor to make the device stand out against its major competitors, but could appeal to power users needing a smartphone with expandable storage and a removable battery due to the exclusion of these features from its main competitor on launch, the [[Samsung Galaxy S6]].<ref name=verge-g4review/><ref name=ars-g4review/>\n\nThe device also became the subject of criticism due to instances of hardware failure caused by manufacturing defects, deemed \"[[LG smartphone bootloop issues|bootloops]]\", which culminated in a class-action lawsuit filed in March 2017.<ref name=\"ars-g4lawsuit\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\n[[File:LG G4 Display.jpg|thumb|200px|The LG G4 Display]]\nThe design of the G4 is an evolution of the G3, maintaining elements such as its rear-located volume and camera buttons. Several back cover options are available, including plastic covers with a diamond pattern and plastic covers coated in [[leather]], stitched down the middle. Six leather color options are available. The G4 features a {{convert|5.5|in|mm|abbr=on}}, [[1440p]]  [[IPS panel|\"Quantum IPS\"]] display, which LG stated would provide better contrast, color accuracy and energy efficiency over another display that LG did not explicitly specify. The G4 utilizes a hexa-core [[Snapdragon (system on chip)#Snapdragon 808|Snapdragon 808]] with 3&nbsp;GB of RAM, consisting of four low-power [[Cortex-A53]] cores and two [[Cortex-A57]] cores.<ref name=verge-g4announce>{{cite web|title=LG's new G4 is a powerhouse phone wrapped in leather|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/4/28/8505589/lg-g4-smartphone-specs-announcement-launch-leather-android|website=The Verge|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=ars-unveil>{{cite web|last1=Amadeo|first1=Ron|title=Hands-on with the leather-backed LG G4|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2015/04/28/hands-on-with-the-leather-backed-lg-g4/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The G4 includes a removable 3000&nbsp;mAh battery and supports Qualcomm [[Quick Charge]] 2.0 technology with a compatible AC adapter, which is not included.<ref name=phonearena-quickcharge>{{cite web|title=LG G4 does have Quick Charge 2.0 capabilities|url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/LG-G4-does-have-Quick-Charge-2.0-capabilities_id69163|website=PhoneArena|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> The G4 comes with 32GB of storage with the option to expand the amount of available storage with a microSD card up to 2&nbsp;TB in size.<ref name=lgg4-specs-us>{{cite web|title=LG G4 Specs|url=http://lg.com/us/mobile-phones/g4/tech_specs|website=LG USA|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe rear-facing camera has a 16-[[megapixel]] sensor with a f/1.8 aperture lens, infrared [[Autofocus#Active|active autofocus]], three-axis [[optical image stabilization]], and LED flash. A \"RGB color spectrum sensor\" is located below the flash, which analyzes ambient lighting to optimize the [[white balance]] and flash color to generate more natural-looking images.<ref name=phonearena-colorspectrumsensor>{{cite web|title=LG G4 color spectrum sensor explained: helps you nail perfect white balance for photos|url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/LG-G4-color-spectrum-sensor-explained-helps-you-nail-perfect-white-balance-for-photos_id68778|website=PhoneArena|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> The front-facing camera is 8-megapixels with an aperture of f/2.0.<ref name=ars-unveil />\n===Software===\nThe G4 is supplied with [[Android Lollipop|Android 5.1 \"Lollipop\"]], although the overall user experience is relatively similar to that of the G3.<ref name=ars-g4review/> The camera software was upgraded with [[raw image]] support, along with a new manual mode offering the ability to adjust the focus, [[shutter speed]], [[Digital camera ISO|ISO]] and [[white balance]]. Optionally, a photo can be taken automatically by double-clicking the lower volume button when the screen is off.<ref name=ars-g4review/> The \"Glance View\" feature allows users to view notifications when the display is off by dragging down.<ref name=\"cnet-g5\">{{cite web|title=LG's next G5 phone to sport 'always on' screen|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/lgs-next-top-end-g5-phone-to-sport-always-on-screen/|website=CNET|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 14, 2015, LG announced that the G4 would be upgraded to [[Android Marshmallow|Android 6.0 \"Marshmallow\"]], with its release beginning in Poland the following week. followed by releases in other European countries, South Korea, and in the U.S. on [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]].<ref name=\"phonearena\"/><ref name=verge-marshmallow>{{cite web|title=LG begins rolling out Android 6.0 Marshmallow to the G4 next week|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/10/14/9536257/lg-g4-marshmallow-update-rollout|website=The Verge|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref> It enables new features such as \"[[Google Now on Tap]]\", which allows users to perform searches within the context of information currently being displayed on-screen, and \"Doze\", which optimizes battery usage when the device is not being physically handled.<ref name=\"ars-review\">{{Cite web|title = Android 6.0 Marshmallow, thoroughly reviewed|url = https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2015/10/android-6-0-marshmallow-thoroughly-reviewed/|work=[[Ars Technica]]|publisher=Conde Nast|accessdate = October 6, 2015}}</ref> By February 2016, it had reached wider distribution, such as in Canada.<ref name=\"phonearena-g4marsh\">{{cite web|title=Android 6.0 Marshmallow update reaches more LG G4 owners|url=http://www.phonearena.com/news/Android-6.0-Marshmallow-update-reaches-more-LG-G4-owners_id77904|website=PhoneArena|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> [[Android Nougat|Android 7.0 \"Nougat\"]] became available for selected models in July 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/lg-g4-android-7-0-nougat-update-available-for-some-models-21492297/|title=LG G4 Android 7.0 Nougat update available for some models|date=2017-07-21|website=SlashGear|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe G4 was met with mixed to positive reception from critics. ''[[The Verge]]'' felt that the G4 could appeal to power users alienated by the removal of expandable storage and replaceable batteries on the then-recently released [[Samsung Galaxy S6]]. The display was praised for its improved color accuracy and energy efficiency over the G3, remarking that it was \"as good, if not better\", than the S6. The G4's rear camera was praised for its quality and color reproduction, along with its \"comprehensive\" manual mode and its \"uncommon\" ability to save [[Raw image format|raw images]], but it was noted that its autofocus sometimes missed focus or took long to achieve focus, and that the manual mode did not offer saturation or sharpness controls. LG's software was criticized for being relatively unchanged from the G3, and for suffering from [[feature creep]] and \"ugly\" aesthetics. The G4 given a 7.9 out of 10, concluding that it \"actually functions just fine \u2014 but you're not going to see it in the hands of every person at the state fair this summer.\"<ref name=verge-g4review>{{cite web|last1=Seifert|first1=Dan|title=LG G4 review: One for the diehards|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/5/6/8559275/lg-g4-review|website=The Verge|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe performance of the LG G4 was contrasted to devices that utilize Qualcomm's Snapdragon 810 (such as the [[LG G Flex 2]]), which was known to have overheating problems. ''[[Ars Technica]]'' felt that the need to throttle CPU-intensive tasks to prevent overheating had a negative effect on the 810's performance, arguing that as a result, the G4's Snapdragon 808 performed better in some cases than the 810 (represented in comparison testing by the [[HTC One M9]]), but that the [[Exynos]] processor of the Galaxy S6 had better overall performance than the two Snapdragon chips on benchmarks. Considering its camera to be the best part of the device, ''Ars Technica'' concluded that the G4 was \"a perfectly competent smartphone, but doesn't really stand out much.\"<ref name=ars-g4review>{{cite web|title=LG G4 Review: More than competent, but less than stunning [Update]|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2015/05/lg-g4-review-more-than-competent-but-less-than-stunning|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Technical problems ===\n==== Touchscreen problems ====\nSome users reported inconsistencies in the performance of the G4's touchscreen, with some units\u2014particularly U.S. T-Mobile and Verizon variants\u2014having problems registering quick taps and swipes. LG released an update to fix the problem in its keyboard app in June 2015, followed by Verizon releasing a major OTA update in November 2015 to fix the touchscreen problems and address other problems with the device.<ref name=\"gbm-fix\">{{cite web|title=LG G4 Touchscreen Problems Fixed in New Update|url=http://www.gottabemobile.com/2015/11/25/lg-g4-touchscreen-problems-fixed-in-new-update/|website=Gotta Be Mobile|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"techtimes-kbfix\">{{cite web|title=LG Outs Fix For LG G4 Touchscreen Issues|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/62417/20150622/lg-outs-fix-for-lg-g4-touchscreen-issues.htm|website=Tech Times|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ndtv-g4touch\">{{cite web|title=Some LG G4 Users Reporting Touchscreen Issues; LG Says It's Investigating|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/some-lg-g4-users-reporting-touchscreen-issues-lg-says-its-investigating-704572|website=Gadgets360|publisher=New Delhi Television|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== \"Bootloop\" hardware failure ====\n{{main article|LG smartphone bootloop issues}}\nIn January 2016, LG confirmed that some G4 units had a manufacturing defect that eventually caused them to enter an unrecoverable reboot loop, resulting from \"loose contact between components\". The company stated that it would repair or replace affected devices under warranty at no charge.<ref name=\"ndtv-g4bootloop\">{{cite web|title=LG Acknowledges G4 Bootloop Issue, Will Repair Affected Units|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/mobiles/news/lg-acknowledges-g4-bootloop-issue-will-repair-affected-units-795410|website=Gadgets360|publisher=New Delhi Television|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ars-g4lawsuit\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, a class-action lawsuit was filed against LG Electronics in the U.S. state of California, alleging that despite acknowledging its existence, LG continued to produce units of the G4 and its sister model, the [[LG V10|V10]], with the defect, and distributed phones that could succumb to the defects as warranty replacements. The lawsuit stated that LG did not [[product recall|recall]] or \"offer an adequate remedy to consumers\" who bought the two models, nor provide any remedy for devices that fell outside of the one-year warranty period.<ref name=\"ars-g4lawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Class-action lawsuit targets LG over legendary G4, V10 bootloop issues|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/03/class-action-lawsuit-targets-lg-over-legendary-g4-v10-bootloop-issues/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> The lawsuit was never certified as a [[class-action lawsuit|class action]], and was sent to [[arbitration]].<ref name=ars-settled>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/02/lg-extends-warranty-to-30-months-for-those-affected-by-bootloop-issue/ |title=Relatively few LG customers will see any money from \"bootloop\" lawsuit |website=Ars Technica |first=Cyrus |last=Farivar |date=February 2, 2018 |accessdate=2018-02-02}}</ref> In January 2018, LG agreed to pay the participants in the lawsuit a $700 credit towards the purchase of a LG smartphone or $425.<ref name=ars-settled/> Since the lawsuit was not certified as a class action, consumers not actually participating in the lawsuit did not receive any payment.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.lg.com/us/mobile-phones/g4}}\n* [https://forum.xda-developers.com/g4/general/guide-tutorial-lg-g4-h815-version-to-t3879698 Howto install Android 7.1 Nougat on LG G4 H815]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = LG G4\n | years  = 2015\n | before = [[LG G3]]\n | after  = [[LG G5]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{LG phones}}\n{{Android phablets}}\n{{Android smartphones}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:LG Electronics mobile phones]]\n[[Cate